On the plus side, the story is clever and leaves me wanting more. An anomaly that actively services the public with something that everyone wants, becoming a norm before the Foundation can contain it. I also admit that the final note generated on each pillar got me; letting the reader hear the note as an advertisement rather than something like  is greatly unsettling. This article makes an attempt at a narrative I haven't seen recently, and it deserves credit for that.

On the downside, the way this article is formatted is actually just a long Discovery:  log, instead of a Description:  . Because of this, there is no actual breakdown of what SCP-3993 is.

I'm settling on a novote for now.

Edit:  If the ratings linger, I sincerely hope you consider rewriting this, author.





